(Ba,Ca)(CO$_{3}$)$_{2}$ comes in a variety of crystal structures (Spahr, 2019): \begin{itemize} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2CD6_mP20_11_e_2e_e_2e2f-001}{monoclinic barytocalcite, space group $P2_1/m$ \#11} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2CD6_hP30_150_e_c2d_f_3g-001}{trigonal paralstonite, space group $P321$ \#150}, \item triclinic alstonite (space group $P1$ \#1 or $P\overline{1}$ \#2) (Sartori, 1975), and \item \href{current_web_home_dir/ABC3_mC10_5_b_a_ac-001}{a new monoclinic structure, space group $C2$ \#5}, synthesized by (Spahr, 2019), and lacking the centrosymmetric character of barytocalcite (the current structure). \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.35in} 
 We used the data using the ``HT synthesis'' results of (Spahr, 2019) while the ICSD entry uses the ``precipitation syntheis'' results. This makes the two CIF files slightly different. 
 The site we have labeled Ba is actually a mixture of barium and calcium atoms.
